Web Scraping

We begin by web scraping sportsoddshistory.com. This website contains historical NFL betting odds data from most of the NFLâs. We will scrape the data for seasons from 2002 to 2023, the season that most recently finished. The data includes betting odds for regular season games and playoff games, including the Super Bowl. The data includes information such as the date, time, teams, betting lines, over/under, and the final score of the game.

Because the seasons from 2002 to 2020 have 17 weeks in the regular season, while the seasons from 2021 to 2023 have 18 weeks, we will scrape the data separately for these two groups of seasons. We will also scrape the playoff data separately for the two groups of seasons.

library(rvest)

# Initialize an empty list to store Week 1 to Week 17
regular_season_2002_2020 <- list()

# Loop through years 2002 to 2020
for(year in 2002:2020) {
  # Construct URL for each year
  url <- paste0("https://www.sportsoddshistory.com/nfl-game-season/?y=", year)
  
  # Read all tables from the URL
  betting <- url |>
    read_html() |>
    html_table()
  
  # Loop through tables from 7 to 23 (Week 1 to Week 17)
  for(week in 7:23) {
    # Name the list element with the corresponding year and week for easier identification
    week_name <- paste0("Year_", year, "_Week_", week - 6)
    
    # Store the table in the list
    regular_season_2002_2020[[week_name]] <- betting[[week]]
  }
}
# Initialize an empty list to store Week 1 to Week 18
regular_season_2021_2023 <- list()

# Loop through years 2021 to 2023
for(year in 2021:2023) {
  # Construct URL for each year
  url <- paste0("https://www.sportsoddshistory.com/nfl-game-season/?y=", year)
  
  # Read all tables from the URL
  betting <- url |>
    read_html() |>
    html_table()
  
  # Loop through tables from 7 to 24 (Week 1 to Week 18)
  for(week in 7:24) {
    # Name the list element with the corresponding year and week for easier identification
    week_name <- paste0("Year_", year, "_Week_", week - 6)
    
    # Store the table in the list
    regular_season_2021_2023[[week_name]] <- betting[[week]]
  }
}
# Initialize an empty list to store Playoff data
playoffs_2002_2020 <- list()

# Loop through years 2002 to 2020
for(year in 2002:2020) {
  # Construct URL for each year
  url <- paste0("https://www.sportsoddshistory.com/nfl-game-season/?y=", year)
  
  # Read all tables from the URL
  betting <- url |>
    read_html() |>
    html_table()
  
  # Directly access the table for Playoffs (table 24)
  playoffs_name <- paste0("Year_", year, "_Playoffs")
  
  # Store the Playoff table in the list
  playoffs_2002_2020[[playoffs_name]] <- betting[[24]]
}
# Initialize an empty list to store Playoff data
playoffs_2021_2023 <- list()

# Loop through years 2021 to 2023
for(year in 2021:2023) {
  # Construct URL for each year
  url <- paste0("https://www.sportsoddshistory.com/nfl-game-season/?y=", year)
  
  # Read all tables from the URL
  betting <- url |>
    read_html() |>
    html_table()
  
  # Directly access the table for Playoffs (table 25)
  playoffs_name <- paste0("Year_", year, "_Playoffs")
  
  # Store the Playoff table in the list
  playoffs_2021_2023[[playoffs_name]] <- betting[[25]]
}

After scraping the data we bind the rows of each list which stacks the data into a single dataframe. We then write the data to a csv file.

Cleaning Home & Away Team Columns

The first step in the data cleaning process is to rename the columns for the home and away teams. We will rename the columns to Favorite_Home and Underdog_Home for both the playoffs and regular season data.

playoffs_2002_2020 <- playoffs_2002_2020 |>
    rename(Favorite_Home = `...7`, Underdog_Home = `...11`)

    rename(Favorite_Home = `...7`, Underdog_Home = `...11`)

    rename(Favorite_Home = `...6`, Underdog_Home = `...10`)

regular_season_2021_2023 <- regular_season_2021_2023 |>
    rename(Favorite_Home = `...6`, Underdog_Home = `...10`)

Next, we use the Faborite_Home column to determine if the favorite team is playing at home, away, or at a neutral site. We will replace the â@â symbol with âHâ for home, NA values to âAâ for away, and âNâ for neutral site.

process_favorite_home <- function(df) {  
  df <- df |>
    mutate(
      Favorite_Home = case_when(
        Favorite_Home == "@" ~ "H",
        is.na(Favorite_Home) ~ "A", # Assumes NA represents 'Away'
        Favorite_Home == "N" ~ "N",
        TRUE ~ Favorite_Home # Keeps original values if none of the above conditions are met
      )
    )
  return(df)
}

Next, we want to rename the source column for both the playoffs and the regular season. For the playoffs, we will use regular expressions to extract the year and then convert it to an integer. process_playoffs <- function(df) {

}

Clean Score Column

Now we will clean the Score column. Currently, the score looks like this: âW 31-29â So, we do a few things here:

  1. Detect if the favorite team won, lost, or tied and create a new column called Result with the corresponding value.
  2. Detect if the game went into overtime and create a new column called Overtime with a 1 if there was overtime and 0 if there wasnât.
  3. Extract the favorite teamâs score and create a new column called Favorite_Score.
  4. Extract the underdog teamâs score and create a new column called Underdog_Score.
  5. Calculate the total points scored in the game and create a new column called Total_Points.
transform_scores <- function(df) {
  df <- df |>
    mutate(
      Result = case_when(
        str_detect(Score, "^W") ~ "W", # Mark 'W' if Favorite won
        str_detect(Score, "^L") ~ "L", # Mark 'L' if Favorite lost
        str_detect(Score, "^T") ~ "T", # Mark 'T' if there was a tie
        TRUE ~ NA_character_ # NA for any unexpected format
      ),
      Overtime = if_else(str_detect(Score, "\\(OT\\)"), 1, 0), # 1 if there's an OT, else 0
      Favorite_Score = as.integer(str_extract(Score, "(?<=^\\w\\s)[0-9]+")), # Extract Favorite score
      Underdog_Score = as.integer(str_extract(Score, "(?<=-)[0-9]+\\b")), # Extract Underdog score
      Total_Points = Favorite_Score + Underdog_Score # Sum of Favorite and Underdog scores
    )
  return(df)
}

regular_season_2002_2020 <- transform_scores(regular_season_2002_2020)

Cleaning Over/Under Column

Using a similar approach to the Score column, we can clean the Over/Under column. The Over/Under column looks like this: âO 45.5â So, we do a few things here:

  1. Detect if the game went over, under, or pushed and create a new column called Over_Under_Result with the corresponding value.
  2. Extract the numeric betting line and create a new column called Betting_Line.
process_over_under <- function(df) {
  
  df <- df |>
    mutate(
      Over_Under_Result = case_when(
        str_detect(`Over/Under`, "^O") ~ "Over",
        str_detect(`Over/Under`, "^U") ~ "Under",
        str_detect(`Over/Under`, "^P") ~ "Push",
        TRUE ~ NA_character_ # Handles unexpected cases
      ),
      Betting_Line = as.numeric(str_extract(`Over/Under`, "[0-9]+\\.?[0-9]*")) # Extracts the numeric betting line
    )
  return(df)
}

regular_season_2002_2020 <- process_over_under(regular_season_2002_2020)
regular_season_2021_2023 <- process_over_under(regular_season_2021_2023)

Cleaning Spread Column

Using a similar approach to the Over/Under column, we can clean the Spread column. The Spread column looks like this: âW -7â So, we do a few things here:

  1. Detect if the favorite team covered, failed to cover, or pushed and create a new column called Favorite_Cover with the corresponding value.
  2. Extract the numeric spread value and create a new column called Spread_Value. If the spread is missing (meaning the game was a âpick-me gameâ), we will impute it with 0.
process_spread <- function(df) {
  df <- df |>
    mutate(
      Favorite_Cover = case_when(
        str_detect(Spread, "^W") ~ "Covered",
        str_detect(Spread, "^L") ~ "Failed",
        str_detect(Spread, "^P") ~ "Push",
        TRUE ~ NA_character_ # Handles unexpected cases
      ),
      Spread_Value = as.numeric(str_extract(Spread, "-?[0-9]+\\.?[0-9]*")) # Extracts the numeric spread value
    ) |>
    mutate(Spread_Value = if_else(is.na(Spread_Value), 0, Spread_Value)) # Impute missing Spread_Value with 0

  return(df)
}

playoffs_2002_2020 <- process_spread(playoffs_2002_2020)
playoffs_2021_2023 <- process_spread(playoffs_2021_2023)
regular_season_2002_2020 <- process_spread(regular_season_2002_2020)
regular_season_2021_2023 <- process_spread(regular_season_2021_2023)

Remove Seed From Playoff Team Names

Next, we will remove the seed from the playoff team names. This is done so that when the data sets are merged, the team names will match up correctly. We do this uing regular expressions.

process_playoff_teams <- function(df) {
  library(dplyr)
  library(stringr)
  
  df <- df |>
    rename(Favorite = `Favorite(Seed)`, Underdog = `Underdog(Seed)`) |>
    mutate(
      Favorite = str_replace(Favorite, " \\(\\d+\\)$", ""), # Removes the seed, e.g., " (4)"
      Underdog = str_replace(Underdog, " \\(\\d+\\)$", "")  # Same for Underdog
    )
  
  return(df)
}

Cleaning Time Related Columns

With a few time related columns, we wanted to make sure we captured proper time stamps correctly, but not overcomplicate the data. Therefore, the first step is to convert the Date column to a Date object and the Time (ET) column to a time object.

Next, we will convert the Time (ET) column to just the hour of the game. This is done so that we can simplify the data and not have to worry about the exact time of the game.

library(dplyr)
library(lubridate)

time_process <- function(df) {
  df <- df |>
    mutate(Date = mdy(Date), # Convert Date from 'Sep 9, 2021' to Date object
           `Time (ET)` = hms(`Time (ET)`)
           )
  return(df)
}

playoffs_2002_2020 <- time_process(playoffs_2002_2020)
playoffs_2021_2023 <- time_process(playoffs_2021_2023)
regular_season_2002_2020 <- time_process(regular_season_2002_2020)
regular_season_2021_2023 <- time_process(regular_season_2021_2023)

# If Time (ET) is at time 1H change to 1, if 2H change to 2, etc.
playoffs_2002_2020 <- playoffs_2002_2020 |>
    mutate(`Time (ET)` = hour(`Time (ET)`))

playoffs_2021_2023 <- playoffs_2021_2023 |>
    mutate(`Time (ET)` = hour(`Time (ET)`))

regular_season_2002_2020 <- regular_season_2002_2020 |>
    mutate(`Time (ET)` = hour(`Time (ET)`))

regular_season_2021_2023 <- regular_season_2021_2023 |>
    mutate(`Time (ET)` = hour(`Time (ET)`))

Renaming Mismatched Team Names

After merging, we noticed that some team names were not consistent across the datasets. This is due to team names changes across the past two decades. We will update the team names to their current names.

# Step 1: Create a mapping of old team names to their current names
team_name_updates <- c(
  'San Diego Chargers' = 'Los Angeles Chargers',
  'Oakland Raiders' = 'Las Vegas Raiders',
  'St Louis Rams' = 'Los Angeles Rams',
  'Washington Redskins' = 'Washington Commanders',
  'Washington Football Team' = 'Washington Commanders'
)

# Step 2: Update the names in both the "Favorite" and "Underdog" columns
all_games_df$Favorite <- plyr::mapvalues(all_games_df$Favorite, from = names(team_name_updates), to = team_name_updates)
all_games_df$Underdog <- plyr::mapvalues(all_games_df$Underdog, from = names(team_name_updates), to = team_name_updates)

Renaming Superbowls to Just Superbowl

We noticed that the Superbowl games were named differently based on what Superbowl it was. We will rename them to just Superbowl for consistency.

all_games_df <- all_games_df |>

Data Exploration

Now that our data is clean, we can begin to explore the data. We will start by plotting each team and their respective cover percentages for both the favorite and underdog roles. This will give us an idea of how well each team performs against the spread.

combined_df <- all_games_df |>
  mutate(Cover_Favorite = case_when(
    Favorite_Cover == 'Covered' ~ 'Covered',
    Favorite_Cover == 'Failed' ~ 'Failed',
    Favorite_Cover == 'Push' ~ 'Push',
    TRUE ~ NA_character_), # Handles unexpected cases
         Cover_Underdog = case_when(
    Favorite_Cover == 'Covered' ~ 'Failed',
    Favorite_Cover == 'Failed' ~ 'Covered',
    Favorite_Cover == 'Push' ~ 'Push',
    TRUE ~ NA_character_)) |>
  select(Team_Favorite = Favorite, Cover_Favorite, Team_Underdog = Underdog, Cover_Underdog) |>
  pivot_longer(cols = c(Team_Favorite, Team_Underdog),
               names_to = "Role",
               values_to = "Team",
               names_prefix = "Team_") |>
  pivot_longer(cols = c(Cover_Favorite, Cover_Underdog),
               names_to = "Cover_Status",
               values_to = "Cover",
               names_prefix = "Cover_") |>
  filter(Role == str_remove(Cover_Status, "_[a-zA-Z]+")) |>
  select(-Cover_Status)

            Failed = sum(Cover == 'Failed') / n() * 100,
            Push = sum(Cover == 'Push') / n() * 100) |>
  ungroup()

As for the models, we will begin by splitting the data into training and testing sets. This is important as we want to train our models on a subset of the data and then test the models on a different subset of the data. This will allow us to see how well our models generalize to new data.

set.seed(123)
data_split <- initial_split(df_model, prop = 0.8, strata = NULL)

training_set <- training(data_split)
testing_set <- testing(data_split)

Furthermore, we will also be splitting the training set into a training and validation set. This will allow us to tune and compare our models on the validation set. The method for obtaining the validation set that will be used is the bootstrap method.

set.seed(123)
bootstrap_set <- bootstraps(training_set, times = 10)

Now lets obtain our workflows for each of our models. The following models will be used and assessed:

  1. A logistic regression, fit using maximum likelihood
  2. A logistic regression, fit using the lasso with a 0.01 penalty
  3. A logistic regression, fit using the lasso with a 0.005 penalty
  4. A k-nearest neighbors model, fit with 10 neighbors
  5. A k-nearest neighbors model, fit with 20 neighbors
  6. A k-nearest neighbors model, fit with 50 neighbors
  7. A k-nearest neighbors model, fit with 100 neighbors
  8. A random forest model, fit using ranger

These workflows are defined below. Keep in mind that in the recipe, we normalized all numeric predictors and created dummy variables for all nominal predictors except for the outcome variable.

log_maxlikelihood <- logistic_reg() |> 
  set_engine("glm") |>
  set_mode("classification")

recipe <- recipe(Favorite_Cover ~ ., data = training_set) |> 
  step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors()) |>
  step_dummy(all_nominal_predictors(), -all_outcomes())

workflow_A <- workflow() |>

Conclusion

Overall, we have successfully trained several types of models and appropriately selected a random forest model as the best performing model. In addition, the hyperparameters that specifies the number of trees in the random forest model was also optimized. The model was then evaluated on the test set and performed better than purely guessing that the favored team would cover the spread. Assuming all odds on bets are -110, the model would have a positive return on investment. However, further optimization in regards to the model and hyperparameters could be done to improve the modelâs performance. In addition, through the ultilization of odds on bets, the model could be further optimized to maximize return on investment.

One staggering limitation throughout this project was the lack of data available. The model could be improved by incorporating player statistics, injuries, and other factors that could influence the outcome of the game. In addition, the model could be further optimized by incorporating odds on bets and maximizing return on investment. In addition, our logistic regression with the lasso penalty model originally was not able to converge. This was due to the high penalty value of 0.1 that was orignally used. Each of the predictor estimates were shrunk to zero, which caused the model to not converge. This was fixed by lowering the penalty value to 0.01 and 0.005.

One final note is that the results we see are exactly what should be expected. A model of our size should not be able to predict the outcome of a game with a high degree of accuracy, it should be aroung 50/50 as that is what the point of the spread is, picking either side you should have a 50% chance of winning. If our model was able to effectively and consistently predict spreads with a high degree of accuracy, then the sportsbooks would not offer spread betting lines. Sportsbooks have models with millions upon millions of trainable parameters. Therefore, again, the results are as expected.
